#Text=Red Lake ( Ontario )
#Text=Red
#Text=Lake
#Text=is a town of 4,100 people ( 2016 ) in Northern Ontario .
#Text=It is a regional transportation hub .
#Text=Understand
#Text=The name of the town comes from a local legend telling of two men from the Chippewa tribe who stumbled across a large moose .
#Text=They then proceeded in killing the moose , the blood of which drained into a nearby lake .
#Text=This turned the lake 's waters red in colour , which gave the area its name . [ 3 ]

#Text=The three primary sources of employment in Red Lake are support services for the numerous mines surrounding the town , small scale logging and a tourism sector specializing in hunting and fishing .
#Text=It is known as the " Norseman Capital of the World " , referring to the Noorduyn Norseman aircraft which played a significant role in the development of the area .
#Text=The town acts as a cargo , passenger and tourism hub for Northwestern Ontario .
#Text=With Pickle Lake , Red Lake serves over twenty northern fly-in communities .
#Text=History
#Text=The First Nations ( Aboriginal ) people are believed to have inhabited the Red Lake area for 2,000 years .
#Text=The first people to live in the land were members of the Sioux and Cree tribes .
#Text=Approximately 200 – 300 years ago the Ojibwe people began to inhabit the area , effectively becoming the predominant people at the time .
#Text=In 1897 , the R.J. Gilbert expedition discovered gold and staked 8 claims .
#Text=However , the remoteness of the site precluded further exploration until 1922 , when the town experienced a sudden surge of economic , industrial , and population growth .
#Text=By 1936 , Red Lake 's Howey Bay was the busiest airport in the world , with more flights landing and taking off per hour than any other .
#Text=In 1995 Goldcorp , owners of the Red Lake Mine , discovered that it contains the world 's richest grade gold ore ( two troy ounces of gold per metric ton ) .
#Text=Shortly thereafter , the mine suffered through a four-year-long miners ' strike .
#Text=Since then , the mine has become one of the richest gold mines in the world .
#Text=Climate

#Text=Snow usually starts falling around late October or early November , and starts melting around March but is not normally fully melted until late April , whilst late-season snow in May is not rare .
#Text=This long winter is ideal for the local snowmobilers and for ice fishing though during this period , although the wind is often very cold and temperatures may drop to below −35 °C or −31 °F .
#Text=During winter , residents and visitors participate in snowmobiling , ice fishing , skiing , ice hockey , and downhill sliding .
#Text=During the summer , the area experiences a moderate climate with little humidity , which is ideal for camping , boating , canoeing , and hiking .
#Text=By plane
#Text=Red Lake Airport ( YRL ) , ☏ +1807 662-2581 , ✉ airport@redlake.ca .
#Text=Regular flights to Dryden , Sioux Lookout , Thunder Bay , and Winnipeg .
#Text=Customs services are not available at this airport .
#Text=Four airway companies take advantage of Red Lake 's close proximity to the northern communities .
#Text=North Star Air , Bearskin Airlines , Superior Airways , and Wasaya Airways operate out of YRL .
#Text=By bus
#Text=Kasper Bus provides bus service to Sioux Lookout , connecting to Thunder Bay and Winnipeg .
#Text=By car
#Text=Take Highway 17 ( the Trans-Canada Highway ) to Vermilion Bay ( west of Dryden ) , then take Highway 105 north for 175 km .
#Text=area . [ 5 ]
#Text=Red Lake is at the northern terminus of Highway 105 .

#Text=A short spur route , Highway 125 , extends northerly from Highway 105 to the communities of Balmertown , Cochenour and McKenzie Island , while Highway 618 extends westerly from Highway 105 to the communities of Madsen and Starratt-Olsen .
#Text=See
#Text=Eco-tourism is becoming popular in the area .
#Text=Red Lake Regional Heritage Centre , 51A Highway 105 , ☏ +1 807-727-3006 , ✉ heritage@redlake.ca .
#Text=M - F 9AM-5PM year round , Sa 10AM-4PM late May to Aug only , closed holidays .
#Text=Heritage museum includes Aboriginal history , the fur trade , aviation and its role in the Red Lake gold rush , and mining .
#Text=There is an exhibition of Woodland art , interactive kids ' displays , and a well-stocked gift shop .
#Text=Adults $ 3 , seniors/students $ 2 , children free .
#Text=Do
#Text=Red Lake is a prime location for summer sport fishing , as the lake contains several types of fish including walleye , northern pike , lake trout , whitefish and sauger .

#Text=Other popular recreational summer activities include golfing at the Red Lake Golf and Country Club , swimming at Rahill and Kinsmen Beach , and even exploring the many bays and arms of Red Lake by boat .
#Text=Hunting attracts tourism , especially during the fall season .
#Text=Red Lake is known for its abundance of game in the district , including moose , ruffed grouse , spruce grouse , duck , and bear .
#Text=The gray wolf , white-tailed deer , red fox , beaver , and many bird species also inhabit the area .
